dvantages of Separating API and Worker:
Independent Scaling: If you have a massive influx of web traffic, you can scale your API containers to 10 instances. If you have thousands of heavy background jobs (like sending emails or processing photos), you can scale your worker containers independently without eating up the API's resources.
Separation of Concerns: The API's only job is to receive an HTTP request, validate it, write/read to the DB, and return a response as fast as possible. The Worker's job is to handle slow, CPU-intensive, or I/O-heavy tasks asynchronously.
Fault Tolerance: If a worker encounters a memory leak or crashes while processing a corrupted image upload, it only takes down that worker container. Your API remains up and continues serving web traffic to your users.
Resource Allocation: You can assign different CPU and RAM limits to them. Workers often need more memory, while APIs need more network throughput.
